According to Jean Baudrillard, we interact&nbsp;
more with what he calls hyper reality than&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:24.400 --> 00:16:30.080
reality itself. To explain what hyperreality&nbsp;
is, I think it's best to just dive into one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:30.080 --> 00:16:36.000
of Baudrillard's examples. Consider the movie&nbsp;
"Apocalypse Now", a film about the Vietnam War.

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:41.840
The acting, the special effects, the sets, the&nbsp;
editing, everything about the film is made so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:41.840 --> 00:16:49.040
that when we watch it on our screen it feels as&nbsp;
real as possible. Heck, it becomes more real than&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:49.040 --> 00:16:55.680
the real war. Most of our understanding of the real&nbsp;
Vietnam War comes from brief video clips online,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:55.680 --> 00:17:02.080
some news articles documenting the big highlights.
Maybe a speech from some politician. But we have no&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:02.080 --> 00:17:08.480
real experience of the real Vietnam War. And the&nbsp;
little bits and pieces we get from the news is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:08.480 --> 00:17:14.480
an extremely watered-down version of the war. They&nbsp;
tell us how many people died, shows short clips of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:14.480 --> 00:17:19.760
soldiers fighting, and innocent residents harmed.&nbsp;
But what about the thousands of stories that go&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:19.760 --> 00:17:26.880
unheard? The film "Apocalypse Now" ends up actually&nbsp;
feeling more real than the real war. When people&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:26.880 --> 00:17:32.400
talk about the Vietnam War, they picture scenes&nbsp;
from the movie rather than the actual war. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:32.400 --> 00:17:40.240
media that was originally an imitation of reality&nbsp;
ends up being more real, thus hyperreal. The hyperreal

00:17:40.240 --> 00:17:45.120
was originally a copy of something real.
But then we start to interact with the hyperreal

00:17:45.120 --> 00:17:52.320
more than reality, and so new forms of media&nbsp;
end up imitating hyperreality rather than reality.

00:17:52.320 --> 00:17:58.640
It becomes a loop of copies, copying copies,&nbsp;
copying copies, until our lives are looking&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:58.640 --> 00:18:05.440
at copies of copies of copies. I believe Stephen&nbsp;
West from Philosophize This! gave an example of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:05.440 --> 00:18:12.960
how TV shows originally drew inspiration from real&nbsp;
people in real lives, but over time new TV shows&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:12.960 --> 00:18:19.840
became inspired by past TV shows. Creating shows&nbsp;
that are now completely detached from reality.

00:18:19.840 --> 00:18:26.400
For instance, How I met your mother or Friends,&nbsp;
comes out and we in real life start to frame what&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:26.400 --> 00:18:33.200
happens to us in relation to these TV shows. We&nbsp;
create character tropes all the time, that we then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:33.200 --> 00:18:39.520
form our real relationships around. Such as people&nbsp;
saying, "I want to be just like Lily and Marshall or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:39.520 --> 00:18:45.360
Monica and Chandler." We see people have magical&nbsp;
love at first sight moments on screen and then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:45.360 --> 00:18:52.800
build expectations of having the same magical&nbsp;
feeling in real life. "I would be forever wed..."&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:54.560 --> 00:19:02.320
The imaginary dictates reality. These expectations&nbsp;
and tropes constrain us in thinking love needs to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:02.320 --> 00:19:08.160
be a certain way, or that if we start off as&nbsp;
the hyper girlfriend, calm boyfriend trope we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:08.160 --> 00:19:15.360
need to maintain that trope. But the thing is,&nbsp;
these expectations and tropes are not based in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:15.360 --> 00:19:21.840
reality. Now how does everything we've talked about&nbsp;
apply to common phrases online? Let's start with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:21.840 --> 00:19:28.400
"if he wanted to he would". Two things about this&nbsp;
mindset bother me. One, it builds the expectation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:28.400 --> 00:19:34.480
that our partners, specifically men, should know&nbsp;
what to do and know what we want without us&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:34.480 --> 00:19:41.360
communicating it. Two, as many people have pointed&nbsp;
out it's literally contradictory. Girls say "if he&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:41.360 --> 00:19:46.960
wanted to he would" and so they don't tell their&nbsp;
man what they want because he should just do&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:46.960 --> 00:19:52.560
it if he wants to, but then if guys had the same&nbsp;
mindset then they would not make the first move&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:52.560 --> 00:19:58.640
either because they're thinking "if she wanted&nbsp;
to, she would." And so no one would do anything.

00:19:58.640 --> 00:20:05.840
Also, sometimes people want to do things but are&nbsp;
not sure if they should are scared, anxious, shy

00:20:14.240 --> 00:20:21.360
or maybe they value your input. Which I really&nbsp;
hope they do. Communication is so, so important.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:21.360 --> 00:20:27.360
If you truly love someone, you would not base your&nbsp;
partner's worth on whether they give you exactly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:27.360 --> 00:20:32.080
what you want. You would care about how much&nbsp;
you're giving them and whether you're both having&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:32.080 --> 00:20:37.920
a reciprocal relationship. Before Valentine's&nbsp;
Day, I saw quite a few TikToks talking about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:37.920 --> 00:20:43.360
how women in heterosexual relationships should&nbsp;
wait to see if their man does something romantic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:43.360 --> 00:20:50.160
for them without saying anything, or if you do say&nbsp;
something you should only mention it once. If your&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:50.160 --> 00:20:56.960
man doesn't do anything or forgets that thing you&nbsp;
had said once, it's a sign to end the relationship.

00:20:56.960 --> 00:21:01.520
"And they know that it's important to you,&nbsp;
you would only have had to say it once, right?

00:21:01.520 --> 00:21:05.920
Because if they loved you they would remember&nbsp;
things that were important to you and it would be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:05.920 --> 00:21:12.880
important to them too. Move in silence on&nbsp;
Valentine's Day. Don't say anything. Hide the gift&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:12.880 --> 00:21:17.760
you're getting them, hide the things that you're&nbsp;
doing for them, not in a manipulative way. Just wait.&nbsp;

00:21:18.400 --> 00:21:27.360
If you walk away from that day disappointed, 
feeling unappreciated, feeling alone, feeling like&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:29.120 --> 00:21:33.840
they're right. it's just a day. It's commercialized.
It doesn't mean anything. They show me they&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:33.840 --> 00:21:37.360
love me every day, so it doesn't really&nbsp;
matter. And I do care about them and I 
do...

00:21:41.360 --> 00:21:49.120
Stop, okay." The thing that bugged me the most is&nbsp;
that these TikToks would say, even if he shows&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:49.120 --> 00:21:56.240
you that he loves you every other day, if he misses&nbsp;
the mark on this one commercialized, arbitrary day,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:56.240 --> 00:22:03.680
then sorry he clearly doesn't love you. There is&nbsp;
so much concern around what can my man do for me,&nbsp;

00:22:03.680 --> 00:22:09.600
can he meet my standards, that this one day can&nbsp;
determine the trajectory of the rest of your&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:09.600 --> 00:22:15.680
relationship? I know it's different for everyone,&nbsp;
maybe your boyfriend has amazing memory and grew&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:15.680 --> 00:22:21.680
up in a loving environment. But for my boyfriend 
and I, we both have a lot going on in our lives&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:21.680 --> 00:22:27.840
And so it's unreasonable to expect us to remember&nbsp;
something someone said once. Just because I forget&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:27.840 --> 00:22:33.120
that he wanted a poke bowl today for dinner, 
does not mean he's not important to me. My&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:33.120 --> 00:22:38.720
boyfriend also grew up in a household without much&nbsp;
celebratory spirit. He didn't receive gifts for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:38.720 --> 00:22:44.880
his Birthday, for Christmas. Him and his friends&nbsp;
never even exchange gifts on special occasions&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:44.880 --> 00:22:50.160
and so is it really fair for me to judge his&nbsp;
love based on what he gives me if he has never&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:50.160 --> 00:22:56.480
been taught to give material gifts? Even as I'm&nbsp;
saying this i understand how hard it can be to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:56.480 --> 00:23:02.000
not let these little things affect you. We are&nbsp;
surrounded by people who post picture perfect&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:08.400
moments of their relationship and it constantly&nbsp;
makes us fixate on how good the love we receive is.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:08.400 --> 00:23:13.760
We are convinced that we should never settle, that&nbsp;
there is some person out there who will give us a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:13.760 --> 00:23:21.520
love as perfect as the ones we see in films and&nbsp;
TV shows. I experience this sometimes too, um, okay&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:21.520 --> 00:23:28.480
that was a lie. I actually experience this all the&nbsp;
time. One of my greatest fears is not being loved,

00:23:29.120 --> 00:23:35.040
so honestly this whole video is almost like&nbsp;
a lecture to myself. I've definitely got a lot&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:35.040 --> 00:23:41.840
to work on in the realm of love, so please don't&nbsp;
think I feel superior to everyone because Iam not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:41.840 --> 00:23:46.960
but that's why it's important to have a good&nbsp;
level of self-love. So that you can squash&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:46.960 --> 00:23:53.360
paranoid worries about not being loved enough and&nbsp;
judge your relationship with a more clear head. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:53.360 --> 00:24:00.640
remember that these movies are not real, they are&nbsp;
hyperreal. The love on your TV screen looks more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:00.640 --> 00:24:07.760
perfect and more real than reality, so it makes&nbsp;
you crave that hyperreality. But it is a mere copy.

00:24:12.080 --> 00:24:18.560
"Red flags" is another term that has gained immense&nbsp;
popularity. I think it is absolutely important to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:18.560 --> 00:24:24.560
watch out for red flags in a relationship but&nbsp;
this term has gotten overused. People watch a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:24.560 --> 00:24:30.880
15 second clip online and suddenly everyone's&nbsp;
got a psychology degree. Here's how author Kim&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:30.880 --> 00:24:37.120
Baker defined red flags. Red flags are whispers&nbsp;
from our intuition that something isn't quite&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:37.120 --> 00:24:42.960
right. A red flag is that sinking feeling we get in&nbsp;
our stomachs when something bad happens. There are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:42.960 --> 00:24:49.440
slivers of evidence usually showing up early on,&nbsp;
that this relationship is not the right one for us.

00:24:49.440 --> 00:24:57.120
A red flag warns that deal breakers are headed our&nbsp;
way. Now I want to place emphasis on deal breakers, 

00:24:57.120 --> 00:25:04.000
something that we absolutely cannot tolerate or is&nbsp;
too much effort to fix. Conversely, not knowing how&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:11.040
to cook or having a perm is not a red flag. That's&nbsp;
just called "not your preference". Don't let random&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:11.040 --> 00:25:17.360
strangers who know nothing about your relationship&nbsp;
control you and tell you what is a red flag. I hope&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:17.360 --> 00:25:23.920
we all dedicate more time to thinking about how&nbsp;
to love others, how to build self-love,  and avoid&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:23.920 --> 00:25:31.280
letting hyperreal displays of love mislead us.
You can like and sub, if you want. Leave a comment&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:31.280 --> 00:25:41.840
if you want. Thank you so much for watching, let's&nbsp;
keep talking and I hope to hear from you soon. Bye!!

